      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical release version documented; FDA in-house FEA code under version control with regression test suite; DePuy Synthes solver qualified per ISO 9001 QMS.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA environments (FDA in-house, Ansys 2022R2, DePuy Synthes internal) operate under documented version control and have passed regression test suites appropriate for structural implicit analysis. Software qualification records on file."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems (cantilever beam, contact patch test) reproduce analytical solutions within 1% for all three codes.",
      "rationale": "Cantilever beam bending and Hertzian contact benchmark problems were executed in all three codes. Deviations from analytical solutions were below 1% in all cases, confirming correct implementation of the relevant element formulations and contact algorithms."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates <2% change in all three QoIs between medium and fine mesh densities.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study (coarse, medium, fine) was performed on the non-cannulated screw–rod construct model. QoI changes between medium and fine meshes were <1.5% for stiffness, <1.8% for yield force, and <1.3% for force at 40 mm. Richardson extrapolation confirmed asymptotic convergence. Production mesh corresponds to the medium density level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual norm at convergence <1e-6 for all load steps; energy balance error <0.1%.",
      "rationale": "Implicit Newton–Raphson solver residual norms were monitored across all load increments. Final residual norms were below 1e-7 in all cases. Energy balance errors were <0.05%. No divergence or spurious contact oscillations were observed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup by second analyst; checklist-based review of boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions documented.",
      "rationale": "An independent second analyst reviewed boundary condition definitions, material property assignments, contact pair definitions, and load application for all three ensemble models. A formal checklist was completed and archived. No discrepancies were identified that affected QoI predictions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum linear-elastic model with frictional contact is appropriate for the pre-yield quasi-static regime; bilinear isotropic hardening captures post-yield response up to 40 mm displacement.",
      "rationale": "The non-cannulated pedicle screw construct is modeled using continuum solid elements with Ti-6Al-4V bilinear isotropic hardening material. Frictional contact (μ=0.2) is applied at screw–rod and rod–set-screw interfaces. Large-deformation (NLGEOM) formulation is active. Model form is consistent with prior FDA validation studies for metallic orthopedic implants under quasi-static loading."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties (E, σ_y, tangent modulus) sourced from certified coupon tests on same material lot as test constructs; geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of production components.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa), yield stress (880 MPa), and tangent modulus (2.2 GPa) were derived from tensile coupon tests on material from the same production lot as the test constructs. Screw and rod geometries were taken from CMM measurements of five production components. Dimensional variability was incorporated via ±1σ sensitivity analysis confirming <3% QoI sensitivity to geometric uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 constructs from production lot; dimensional verification by CMM; material certification traceable to mill certificates.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from production-lot components. Each construct was dimensionally verified by CMM prior to testing. Material certifications (mill certificates) were obtained for all metallic components. Constructs were distributed across two independent laboratories to assess inter-laboratory variability."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicate ASTM F1717 protocol including load angle, fixture geometry, displacement rate, and environmental conditions; multiple test conditions (load angles) preferred.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted per ASTM F1717 at a single compression-bending load angle (5°). While the protocol was rigorously followed and environmental conditions (ambient temperature, humidity) were recorded and consistent across both laboratories, only one load angle was evaluated. This limits the generalizability of the validation to the specific F1717 test configuration. Achieved level is 2 (below required level of 3); this gap is acknowledged and accepted given that the COU is specifically the F1717 test configuration."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions, geometry, and material inputs demonstrably derived from the same sources as the physical test setup; traceability matrix documented.",
      "rationale": "A traceability matrix maps each FEA model input (geometry, material, boundary conditions, load angle, fixture stiffness) to the corresponding experimental measurement or specification. Fixture stiffness was measured and incorporated into the FEA model as a spring boundary condition. Load application point and angle were verified against physical fixture drawings."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using E/uval metric (acceptance: E/uval < 1.96) and percent difference (<10%) for all three QoIs across all ensemble members.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric E/uval was computed for construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement for each of the three ensemble models. All nine E/uval values were below 1.96. Percent differences between FEA predictions and experimental means were below 10% for all QoIs. Force–displacement curves were also compared qualitatively and showed excellent agreement in both elastic and post-yield regimes."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to clinical failure modes (fatigue initiation, permanent deformation) and are the same outputs used in the regulatory submission.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load sharing with the spine and is linked to adjacent segment disease risk. Yield force and force at 40 mm displacement bound the onset of permanent deformation and are directly used in the fatigue safety factor calculation in the regulatory submission. All three QoIs are specified in the V&V plan and are the same outputs evaluated in the COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario (non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw, ASTM F1717, two-level construct) matches the COU scenario with respect to device design, loading mode, and regulatory context.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly tests the FEA model of the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct under the identical ASTM F1717 compression-bending protocol that defines the COU. The same model ensemble, same component geometry, and same material lot are used in both the validation and the intended regulatory submission. Validation relevance is rated highest achievable given the direct correspondence between validation scenario and COU."
    }
  ],
